Let the two numbers be $x$ and $y$, where $x>y$. We wish to find $x$. The problem can be rewritten as the system of equations: \begin{align*}
x+y&= 22\\
x-y&= 4
\end{align*} Adding these gives: \begin{align*}
2x &= 26\\
x &=\boxed{13}.
\end{align*}

\[
\begin{array}{c|cc cc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{x} & -5 \\
\cline{2-5}
x^2 + 5x + 1 & x^3& & &  \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{x^3} & +5x^2 & +x  \\
\cline{2-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -5x^2 & -x & \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -5x^2 & -25x & -5 \\
\cline{3-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 24x & +5 \\
\end{array}
\]Thus, the remainder is $\boxed{24x + 5}.$

To solve for $x$, we wish to eliminate $y$. Multiply the first equation by $2$ and add it to the second: \begin{align*}
(4x-2y) + (x+2y) &= 10+5\\
5x &= 15\\
x &= \boxed{3}
