answer:
When using the distributive property for the first time, we add the product of $2p^2 - 1$ and $3p^2$ to the product of $2p^2 - 1$ and $4$:

\begin{align*}
(2p^2 - 1)(3p^2 + 4) &= (2p^2 - 1) \cdot (3p^2) + (2p^2 - 1) \cdot 4
\end{align*}We use the distributive property again and combine like terms:

\begin{align*}
(3p^2)(2p^2 - 1) + 4(2p^2 - 1) &= 6p^4 - 3p^2 + 8p^2 - 4\\
&= \boxed{6p^4 + 5p^2 - 4}
\end{align*}

question:
Expand and simplify completely: \begin{align*}
x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*}

answer:
Begin by distributing in the innermost parentheses: \begin{align*}
&\ \ \ \ x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2) \\&= x(x+x^2+2x) - 3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*} Now, distribute again: \begin{align*}
x^2+x^3+2x^2-3x^2+3x-6
\end{align*} Finally, combine like terms to get \begin{align*}
\boxed{x^3+3x-6}
\end{align*}

